vectorData.altText: That's right! Notice the middle cerebellar peduncles reaching posteriorly for the cerebellum and the fourth ventricle between them. Notice the belly of the pons ventrally.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

In Functional Neuroanatomy, in the Spinal Cord and Brainstem series, compare sections 12 (midpons) and 11 (caudal pons) to axon-stained sections of the midpons and caudal pons that I provided. In these images, identify the belly of the pons arching ventrally. Notice how this time the cerebellar peduncles reach posteriorly toward the cerebellum with the 4th ventricle in between.  
Now look at Transverse Series of MRIs, sections 6 (midpons) and 5 (caudal pons), and identify the same features.
This characteristic shape, with the belly of the pons arching anteriorly, and the cerebellar peduncles reaching posteriorly with the 4th ventricle in between, identifies the pons in MRI.
Some say that a cross section of the caudal pons reminds them of Darth Vader.
Be sure you can identify features A through C. See answers here     .
